Notice Issued on Convocation of SPA Session 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, March 22 (KCNA) -- The Presidium of the DPRK Supreme People's Assembly issued a notice on Mar. 21 informing the deputies of its decision to call the fourth session of the 11th SPA on April 11, Juche 95 (2006), in Pyongyang.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Deputies to the SPA are requested to register their names at the Mansudae Assembly Hall on April 9 and 10, Juche 95 (2006), it said.

Korean People's Struggle Supported 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Havana, March 20 (KCNA) -- Juan Jose Leon Vega, chairman of the Cuban Committee for Supporting Korea's Reunification, at an annual meeting of the committee held in Havana on March 17, said that last year the committee held functions on a high level to strengthen friendship and solidarity with the Korean people on such important occasions as the birth anniversary of President Kim Il Sung, the birthday of leader Kim Jong Il and the June 25-July 27 month of the anti-U.S. joint struggle.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 He raised the tasks to positively support the Korean people's struggle this year marking the 80th anniversary of the formation of the Down-with-Imperialism Union by Kim Il Sung.

Annual Meeting of Korea-Cuba Solidarity Committee Held 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, March 22 (KCNA) -- An annual meeting of the Korea-Cuba Solidarity Committee was held at the Taedonggang Club for the Diplomatic Corps on Tuesday.
 Present there were Minister of Education Kim Yong Jin who is chairman of the Korea-Cuba Solidarity Committee, Vice-Chairman of the Korean Committee for Cultural Relations with Foreign Countries Jon Hyon Chan and members of the solidarity committee. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Also on hand were Ruben Perez Valdes, Cuban ambassador to the DPRK, and embassy officials. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The meeting reviewed the last one-year-long work of the committee for friendship and solidarity with the Cuban people who are defending the sovereignty of the country and the gains of revolution under the leadership of the Communist Party of Cuba headed by Fidel Castro Ruz, supreme leader of the Cuban revolution, and discussed an action program for this year.

U.S. Urged to Drop Its Arbitrary and High-handed Diplomacy
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, March 22 (KCNA) -- The results of the votes for the resolution on the establishment of the new Human Rights Council clearly prove that the U.S. arbitrary and high-handed diplomacy is going bankrupt and the UN is no longer a plaything of the U.S. unilateral high-handed diplomacy, says Rodong Sinmun Wednesday in a signed commentary.
 Recalling that the U.S. could not achieve its objective when voting was done on the resolution on the creation of the above-said council at the plenary session of the UN General Assembly, the commentary goes on: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The U.S. worked craftily to convert the new body into a platform where politicization, the application of double standards and high-handed and arbitrary practices prevail in handling human rights issues from the very day the issue of creating the body was put high on the agenda. One may draw a conclusion from the voting outcome that gone are the days when the U.S. could lord it over the international arena, dictating this or that, and it is finding itself in the mire of international isolation.
 Today things are not going on as the U.S. wishes and desires and its high-handed and arbitrary practices get it nowhere. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 It is the human rights situation in the world today that any crime committed by the strong is considered as a good deed while a good deed made by the weak is regarded as an evil doing. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Therefore, it is hard to vouch that the creation of a new Human Rights Council to replace the UN Commission on Human Rights would put an end to the politicization of human rights issues, the application of double standards and high-handed and arbitrary practices as regards those issues. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Now that the reform of the human rights body has entered the phase of implementation, it is necessary to bring about a fundamental change in the UN's activities to protect human rights and improve their performance. The new council should impartially handle human rights issues on the universally accepted principle of respect for one's sovereignty and thus make a substantial contribution to improving the human rights performance.

Japanese Reactionaries Urged to Behave Themselves
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, March 22 (KCNA) -- The Japanese reactionaries are escalating their frantic racket of confrontation with the DPRK, while letting a spate of malignant vituperation at it. They would be well advised to behave themselves with reason. 
 This warning is served again by Minju Joson Wednesday in a signed commentary.
 They are persistently raising the "abduction issue" which had already been settled and citing it as a good pretext for stepping up their hostile policy toward the DPRK, the commentary observes, and goes on: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 It is as clear as noonday that Japan will kick off a confrontation racket against the DPRK over this issue in the future, too when necessary. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 No wonder, the world public notes with concern that it will be hard to expect any improvement in the relations between the DPRK and Japan in case such candidate from the conservative forces in Japan as Chief Cabinet Secretary Abe comes to power in September. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The Japanese ultra-right conservative politicians calculate that confrontation and pressure will work on the DPRK. However, this is as foolish a calculation as betraying their political ignorance. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The noisy anti-DPRK racket of the Japanese reactionaries will only lead the situation to catastrophe. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The above-said hysteria of the Japanese reactionaries is only triggering off bitterer hatred for Japan among the servicepersons and people in the DPRK. No one can vouch that this will not reach the point of explosion. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 In this case, Japan will be held wholly accountable for this.

World Water Day Observed
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, March 22 (KCNA) -- Minju Joson today dedicates an article to World Water Day.
 Reviewing the energetic drive to preserve water resources in various fields in the DPRK, the author of the article says: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The preservation of water resources is legally guaranteed. Noteworthy in this connection is the adoption of the "Law on water resources in the DPRK" in 1997. Work for a rational use and protection of water resources has gone on full blast under the concern of the state, typical of which is the building of reservoirs for the supply of drinking water and the already completed Kaechon-Lake Thaesong waterway and Paekma-Cholsan waterway. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
  In the meantime, projects to improve the control of swamp resources and river basins are being energetically pushed on in close contact with international organizations including the UNDP, the Global Environment Facility and the World Conservation Union. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 We will satisfactorily solve the water problem by steadily improving the preservation and control of the water resources in the future in keeping with the intrinsic demand of the Korean-style socialist system under which man is most valued in the world.

Water Resources Protected in DPRK
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, March 22 (KCNA) -- Water resources have been well protected and managed in the Democratic People's Republic of Korea.
 Today the water problem has been raised as a serious social, economic and political issue on a world-wide scale owing to the rapid growth of population, environmental pollution, global warming, ever-increasing demand for water arising from socio-economic development and so on. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 An international body made an announcement that the per capita yearly volume of water resources should amount to 5,00    10,000 cubic meters. The DPRK in which the yearly water volume per capita is 2,900 cubic meters has also directed due efforts to solve the problem of insufficient water. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The government is conducting in a perspective way the work for the protection and sustainable development of water resources on the basis of the water resources law, environmental protection law, land law and the principle of payment by contaminator while increasing state investment in this field every year. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Steps have been taken for making an effective use of water resources. They include construction of reservoirs on upper reaches of rivers and streams with a large amount of rainfall and rich water resources and large and minor hydro-power stations in different parts of the country including the Anbyon Youth Power Station and the establishment of a unified water commanding system and proper water control and management system. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Gravity-fed waterways including Kaechon-Lake Thaesong Waterway and Paekma-Cholsan Waterway have come into being, making water resources distributed rationally in various places of the country. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Meanwhile, an early warning system was established for the purpose of correctly forecasting in time the water volume flowing into rivers and reservoirs in each season, month and ten-days and flood during the rainy season and preventing damage.
 Afforestation, river improvement and other land management campaigns have been launched every spring and autumn. And efforts are being concentrated on putting water resources management on a computerized and scientific basis. 
 On the World Water Day (March 22), colorful activities calling for protecting and managing well water resources and saving water are being conducted among people.

Promising Female Footballer
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, March 22 (KCNA) -- FIFA (International Football Federation) made public the lists of ten best football players (men and women) of the year 2005 in October last year.
 Among the women players is Ho Sun Hui of the DPRK. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 She, hailing from Kilju County, North Hamgyong Province, started to learn basic soccer technique at the age of 12 with a special interest in football.
 She acquired the basic soccer technique and prepared herself physically in a short span of time with her assiduous and energetic efforts. Already at the age of 15, she distinguished herself in the female football world, drawing the attention of experts.
 She, active as a member of the state selected football team from 6 years ago, did her bit to making the DPRK women's football team win championships in the 13th and 14th Asian Female Football Championships in succession and take the first place in the women's football tournaments of the 14th Asian Games. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Her specialty is skilful game organization and powerful medium and long distance kick. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 She was awarded the title of Merited Athlete in Juche 92(2003).
 Ho told KCNA that she would further intensify training and thus do her duty as an athlete of Songun Korea to the expectation of the fatherland and people.

Brisk Physical Culture and Sports
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, March 22 (KCNA) -- Physical culture and sports activities are getting brisk in the Democratic People's Republic of Korea as spring comes.
 Seen everywhere in the country are people, young and old, who are doing morning exercises including running, walking and Taekwon-Do. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Physical culture and sports events were held in Pyongyang and other parts of the country on the Day of Sports for March with the attendance of working people of various strata and school children and youth. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 In the DPRK, the second Sunday of every month has been instituted as the Day of Sports. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 On the day, physical culture and sports events are held at institutions, enterprises, co-op farms and schools. Among the events are health-promoting Taekwon-Do, mass rhythmic gymnastics, collective running and tug of war. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Mass sports activities are held. Typical of them are the traditional sports contests of officials of the national institutions for Paektusan Cup, national Korean wrestling matches for Grand Bull Prize, national folk sports games of agricultural working people. 
 The physical culture and sports games held in different areas of the country are introduced through mass media. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 All the working people's organizations including the youth league and trade unions are inducing working people, youth and children to take part in the mass physical culture activities on their own accord so that they can build their bodies and firmly prepare themselves for national defence and labor. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The brisk mass physical culture and sports activities give a glimpse of revolutionary stamina and optimism pervading the whole country.

Greetings to Prime Minister of Pakistan
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, March 22 (KCNA) -- Pak Pong Ju, premier of the DPRK cabinet, sent a message of greetings to Shaukat Aziz, prime minister of Pakistan, on the occasion of the day of Pakistan, the national holiday of the Pakistani people.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The message sincerely wished him and the government of Pakistan greater successes in their work for the development and prosperity of the country, expressing the conviction that the friendly and cooperative relations between the two countries would grow stronger.

Greetings to Pakistani President
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, March 22 (KCNA) -- Kim Yong Nam, president of the Presidium of the DPRK Supreme People's Assembly, Wednesday sent a message of greetings to General Prevez Musharraf, president of Pakistan, on the day of Pakistan, the national holiday of the Pakistani people.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Wishing him greater success in his responsible work for the prosperity of the country and the well-being of the people, Kim Yong Nam expressed the belief that the friendly and cooperative relations between the two countries would grow stronger.

Congratulations to Libyan VIPs
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, March 22 (KCNA) -- Premier of the DPRK Cabinet Pak Pong Ju sent a congratulatory message to Al Baghdadi Ali Al Mahmoudi on the latter's appointment as secretary of the General People's Committee of the Great Socialist People's Libyan Arab Jamahiriya at the recent General People's Congress.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The message wished him great success in his responsible work for the prosperity of the country, expressing the belief that the friendly and cooperative relations between the two countries would grow stronger. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Foreign Minister Paek Nam Sun sent a similar message to Abdulrahman Mohamed Shalgham upon the latter's reappointment as secretary for Foreign Liaison and International Cooperation of Libya.

April Spring Friendship Art Festival to Be Held
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, March 22 (KCNA) -- The 24th April Spring Friendship Art Festival will be held in Pyongyang on the occasion of the Day of the Sun.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The festival will register another special chapter in its history as it will also prove to be a great international art festival which will fully reflect the unanimous desire and wishes of the world progressives and artistes to hold President Kim Il Sung in high esteem forever and hand down his undying feats to the posterity through such colorful numbers as songs, instrumental music, dances and circus pieces.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 It will bring together dozens of art and circus groups made up of famous artistes of different countries including winners of international and national concours and Korean art groups overseas and at home. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The festival, which will draw capacity audiences at different theatres and halls of Pyongyang, will contribute to boosting the friendly bonds and strengthening and developing the cultural exchange and cooperation among peoples and artistes of different countries.

Reunion of Separated Families and Relatives Held
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Mt. Kumgang Resort, March 22 (KCNA) -- The 13th reunion of separated families and relatives was held at Mt. Kumgang resort under the agreement reached at the 17th inter-Korean ministerial talks and the meeting that took place between the Red Cross organizations of the north and the south of Korea.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Separated families and relatives of the north had a group reunion with their kinsmen from the south on March 20. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 They, greatly rejoiced at meeting with their kinsmen whom they have longed to see even in dreams, talked to each other about the course of their life, inquired after the health of those who were not able to join them and exchanged tidings of their relatives.
 Families and relatives of the north told kinsmen from the south that they have fully enjoyed a worthwhile life and devoted themselves to the prosperity of the country, helping and leading each other forward like members of a big family in the grateful socialist system under the warm care of leader Kim Jong Il. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Families and relatives of the north and the south ardently called for pooling efforts in their efforts to hand down without fail the reunified country to the generations to come.
 That day, the Central Committee of the Red Cross Society of the DPRK arranged a reception in honor of the separated families and relatives of the north and the south.
 Families and relatives of the north toured the area of Samil Lagoon, a scenic spot, together with kinsmen from the south on Tuesday. They had family reunions at which they posed for photographs and exchanged long pent-up inmost thoughts.
 They bid farewell to each other, promising themselves to work together for national reunification under the banner of the historic June 15 joint declaration on Wednesday.
 The reunion continues.

Kim Jong Il Inspects Sub-Units of KPA Unit
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, March 22 (KCNA) -- Supreme Commander of the Korean People's Army Kim Jong Il, general secretary of the Workers' Party of Korea and chairman of the National Defence Commission of the DPRK, inspected sub-units of KPA Unit 604.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 He acquainted himself with the unit's performance of duty before watching its servicepersons' firepower training. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 After watching the training replete with the spirit of winning a sure victory, he expressed great satisfaction over the fact that all the soldiers of the unit have been fully prepared as indomitable fighters capable of reliably defending the security of the country and the people. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 He highly appreciated the shining achievements made by the servicepersons of the sub-units in the past, noting that they have grown to be matchless combat ranks fully prepared politically and ideologically and in military technique through the strenuous efforts to carry through the military line of the WPK. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Then he took warm care of the living of their servicepersons, going round an education room, a bedroom, a mess hall, a kitchen, a wash-cum-bath house, a non-staple food store, an outdoor resting place and other places. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 No details escaped him, ranging from entertainment and educational means and bedroom conditions to the processing of non-staple food and its variety and the quality of water in the wash-cum-bath house. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Saying that TV sets and VCRs which the soldiers like to watch serve as good fellow travelers, he underscored the need to make a regular use of these important educational means so that they may watch films and keep abreast of news from the rear.
 He called on all the commanding officers to take care of the living of the soldiers with paternal love just as the commanding officers of the anti-Japanese guerrilla army did and thus provide better living conditions to the servicepersons whom the WPK values and loves so much. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 He had a photo session with the servicepersons of the sub-units. 
 He was accompanied by Hwang Pyong So, vice department director of the WPK Central Committee.
